s affecting communities in remote or neglected areas, is now concentrating on three major fields.
\par Dr Nevill, who has teamed up with other experts to publish some leading research papers on various aspects of malaria, says that communities are involved in the manufacture , use and sale of bednets impregnated with insecticides.
\par AMREF also aims at preventing malaria-related anaemia which is common in western and coastal regions of Kenya. Malaria related anaemia has been one of the major causes of blood transfusions in some parts of the country.
\par Dr Nevill's unit also collaborates with others, like the Kenya Medical Research Institute, to determine new anti-malaria drugs that are cheap and effective because the drugs used against resistant malaria are expensive. 
This includes trying out new combinations of some of the "old" drugs that have been discarded.
