\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Cancer patients whose illness has reached a stage at which there is no longer hope for cure and that death may be close should not be left to die in pain, }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Raphael Kahaso }{\fs24\lang2057 reports.
\par <#/>An eleven-year-old child walks into the Nairobi Hospice at the Kenya
tta General Hospital accompanied by his parents. <#/>As they sit down to wait for their turn to see the doctor, they chat happily glancing now and then at the door to the consultation room.
\par <#/>When their turn to see the doctor comes, the boy struggles to stand up. <#/>He is assisted by the parents and they walk to the consultation room.
\par <#/>Dr Anne Merriman examines the boy, asks a few questions and writes down the prescription. <#/>The father goes to the Hospice's pharmacy to get the prescribed drugs.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>The boy is one of the cancer patients referred to the Hospice as their illness has reached the stage at which there is no longer hope for cure and that death may be close.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{\fs24 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Cancer </}{\fs24\lang2057 h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The boy's parents have come to accept that soon their boy will be taken away by cancer, never to see him until they meet again in heaven. <#/>They have been counselled to accept the inevitable.
\par <#/>The boy is the youngest cancer patient to be attended to at the Hospice which is also known as the Nairobi Terminal Care Centre. <#/>The oldest patient is in his 80's.
\par <#/>And since the Nairobi Terminal Care Centre opened its door in March 1990, 85 cancer patients who have reached a stage at which there is no hope for cure have been attended to. <#/>Of that number only 22 are still alive.
\par <#/>Unlike hospitals which concentrate on curative measures, the Nairobi Terminal Care Centre gives "palliative" or "terminal" care meant to relieve pain and the distressing symptoms of the disease.
\par <#/>Dr Anne Merriman, the Health Services Co-ordinator, who is a full-time doctor at the Hospice, says the institution has simple inexpensive methods to ease pain and to allow the incurably ill }{\b\fs24\lang2057 <+_to>}{\fs24\lang2057  die with dignity.

\par <#/>The Hospice approach involves counselling of both the patient and his immediate relatives about the inevitable that is soon to happen to the patient so that all parties involved may be psychologically prepared.
\par <#/>Sometimes cancer patients are referred to the Hospice two or three days before death occurs. <#/>By this time the patient has suffered immensely from excessive pain.
\par <#/>Pain, according to Dr Merriman is the most expected and the most feared symptom for cancer patients. <#/>It occurs in one-third of patients receiving anti-cancer therapy, but in more than two thirds of patients with advanced disease.
\par <#/>This physical pain can be made worse by emotional suffering, social problems, depressions and anxiety. <#/>If advanced cancer cannot be treated, the pain can be treated, she said.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<X_>}{\v The treatment of the pain may be
 started with non-opioid analgesics such as aspirin or paracetamol, then progresses to the use of mild opioids such as codeine and, if pain persists, strong opioids such as morphine until the patient is free of pain.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v\fs24\lang2057 Once pain control is established, the drugs are given "by the clock", that is, regularly from every three to six hours, according to the individual patient's needs.
\par Dr Merriman says that <-/upto> 95 per cent of the pain of incurably cancer patients }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\v\fs24\lang2057  can be controlled to enable the patients }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_to>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
 "have life into their days, not just days into their life".
\par Morphine, however is expensive and has to be imported from Singapore. Many of the 22 cancer patients under the Hospice programme, need morphine to control the extreme pain. A supply of morphine for 10 days costs Shs 3.000 per patient.
\par Morphine is processed from poppy opium. This has to be imported as the laws of Kenya do not permit the growing of poppy opium.
\par In October 1989 a plantation of poppy opium was discovered in Kiambu District by officers from the Criminal Investigation Department headquarters. Several farmers were arrested.
\par Grown legally, poppy opium provides cooking oil and tasty seeds, helps to condition the soil for food crops, and is the source of the modern world's standard against which all pain is measured.
\par Grown illegally, poppy opium is a source of misery, the plant 
whose milky, alkaloid-rich sap becomes, with chemical processing a shortcut to euphoria but, long term, a downhill road to addiction, horror, crime and death according to National Geographical Society.
\par The fact that the Hospice spends a fortune to import m
orphine underlines the importance of legalising the growing of poppy opium, at least on a small scale to produce enough for processing into morphine. This would save the patients, the relatives and the Nairobi Terminal Care Centre a lot of worry anxiety a
nd money.
\par Nairobi Terminal Care Centre's monthly budget of Shs 300,000 mainly goes towards the purchase of the pain relieving drugs, mainly morphine.
\par Patients are advised to buy the drugs from the Hospice's <-/phrmacy> but those who are unable to pay are asked to pay what they can afford. This means that the centre has to rely on charity and good will of the members of the public.
\par With a full time staff of seven employees, the centre is capable of serving the needs of the incurably ill but it has been found to be inadequate as it lacks ward facilities where patients can be admitted.
\par Some of those patients who live in areas where the Hospice staff can't visit them could be admitted in wards if a more spacious hospice was built.
\par There are plans, according to a 
reliable source to construct a more spacious hospice that will have facilities for 25 beds where the critically ill cancer patients may be admitted. Here the patients would be able to be visited by their relatives any time for comfort.
\par Such a spacious hospice according to Dr Anne Merriman would require about Shs 80 million to construct and an annual running cost of Shs 16 million.
\par Cancer is increasing in the population in Kenya. It is estimated that more than 3,000 new cases of cancer are diagnosed every ye
ar and about 20 per cent of all adults and 10 per cent of children admitted to Kenyatta National Hospital, the central referral and the largest in Kenya, have problems relating to cancer.
\par By the time cancer patients go to hospital for treatment, the disease is at an advanced stage. In 70 per cent of such patients the disease is too advanced for surgery or radiotherapy and chemotherapy to be able to cure.
\par These are the patients whom doctors at provincial hospitals refer to the Hospice. In the past such relatives of such a patient would be advised to "take the patient home as there is no treatment".
\par Today there may not be treatment for the disease but treatment for the pain and doctors are now being trained on }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>prep}{\v\fs24\lang2057  the Hospice approach to relieve such patients }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_from>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057  the much pain they suffer.
\par A doctors' course on the Hospice approach has now been launched at provincial level. The first such course will be held in Eldoret for doctors in the Uasin Gishu District before the end of November. Eldoret Hospital
 is being upgraded to a teaching hospital.
\par The idea is to expose all the doctors and nurses to the Hospice approach so that cancer patients whose imminent death is a matter of time, may be able to get the necessary drugs to control pain.
\par The idea of the Hospice approach training is to enable the health authorities to start mini hospice centres where such patients may be supplied with drugs to control their pain. }{\fs24\lang2057 </X>
