\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>After looking at the kinds, causes and risks of obesity, our net major concern is how to control and treat obesity.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The current methods include, 
\par * diet,
\par * exercise,
\par * psychotherapy,
\par * behaviour modification, 
\par * <-/phamacology> or drugs, 
\par * surgery.
\par <#/>Pertaining to weight reduction most people are interested in easy and quick methods. <#/>Hence the consumer has become easy prey for those providing magical ways of losing weight which promise something for nothing.
\par <#/>As we discuss the methods, keep in mind that there are some poor and some good choices.
\par <#/>The producers and advocates of water pills hold that excess weight is due to water accumulation. <#/>Indeed temporary water retention, seen in many women around
 the time of the menstrual period may make a difference of a number of kilos on the scale. <#/>Oral contraceptives may also promote actual fat gain in some people.
\par <#/>If water retention is a problem, it can be <-/diagonised> by a medical doctor who may pr
escribe a "water pill" (diuretic) and probably some restriction of salt (sodium) in your diet. <#/>However, the over fat has a smaller percentage of water than a normal person in weight. <#/>Hence if the obese takes a self prescribed diuretic she/he has d
one nothing to alleviate her fat problem despite the fact that she may <-/loose> some weight on the scale for half a day and may suffer from dehydration.
\par <#/>Some dieters take pills e.g. amphetamines to assist with weight loss.
\par <#/>These drugs have been shown to depress the appetite, but only temporarily. <#/>The appetite returns to normal after a week or so and the lost weight might be regained.
\par <#/>These drugs also cause dangerous dependency or "addiction". <#/>They may cause insomnia or loss of sleep, excitability and dry mouth. <#/>With this we can conclude that they (amphetamines) are of little use in weight control if at all they have any.

\par <#/>Also }{\i\fs24\lang2057 fenfluamine}{\fs24\lang2057  or }{\i\fs24\lang2057 phentermine}{\fs24\lang2057  has its own <-/soide> effects.
\par <#/>In some cases where there is no hypothroidism, thyroid <-_hormone><+_hormones> have been used. <#/>This hormone is expensive and not easily available and may cause loss of lean mass instead of fat.
\par <#/>Many other drugs have been used with the manufacturers claiming that they inhibit food absorption or synthesis in the body. <#/>Side effects are severe and many have been reported to be a health hazard.
\par <#/>One more known appetite depressant is cigarette smoking but we need not <-/delobour> its obvious hazards.
\par <#/>The health spa benefits from people's desire to <-/loose> weight and keep fit. <#/>These facilities can be used to your advantage. <#/>If you really exercise you reap the benefits.
\par <#/>But spas can be really  expensive and the unsuspecting consumer may fall for gimmicks that offer no real health advantages than the psychological boost.
\par <#/>Hot baths do not speed up your calorie expenditure at rest (basal metal bolic rate). <#/>Steam and sauna baths do not melt the fat off. <#/>What the two have i
n common is that they cause you to sweat and dehydrate, thus making dramatic weight reduction on the <-/scale>.
\par <#/>Machines that promise to jiggle your fat off while you lean passively on the machine provide only pleasant stimulation, no exercise and no fat reduction.
\par <#/>There is a fallacy about two kinds of fat. <#/>Regular fat and cellulite. <#/>Cellulite is said to be a hard lumpy fat that only disintegrates on burning up, it is said that only such methods as massage or hot spa can decompose them. <#/>
It is true that sometimes fat will appear lumpy due to connective tissue attaching the skin to the underlying structure. <#/>However the above claim is nothing but a hoax.
\par <#/>Two major surgical operations undertaken in reference to weight control are.
\par <#/
>Stomach stapling (or gastric <-/hypass> or gastroplasty) <-/by passes> a certain portion of the stomach. <#/>It is achieved by the "stapling" of the stomach to make it smaller. <#/>This forces the person to eat less food. <#/>Though pleasingly simple sou
nding, there have been reports of staples pulling loose. <#/>One should always think long and hard before submitting to it, for it damages stomach tissue and also forms scars.
\par <#/>Jejunoileal bypass involves disconnecting a portion (=90%) of the small intes
