\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <I> <h> }{\fs24 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Why pregnant women eat soil }{\fs24\lang2057 </h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{\fs24 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Some get so drawn to the habit that they eventually get addicted }{\fs24\lang2057 </h}{\b\fs24\lang2057 >
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Of all the delicacies, tuff is one that is least discussed. <#/>But its addicts crave for it as much as smokers crave for cigarettes and alcoholics for beer.
\par <#/>Tuff is a kind of clay that many pregnant women love to chew. <#/>Some get so drawn into the habit that they actually get addicted to it. <#/>They can smell it from a distance. <#/>This makes it easy for them to look for it.
\par <#/>Peterson Kamotho Gachago of the University of Nairobi says tuff is a geological name give to volcanic soil which is solidified.
\par <#/>Gachago is a postgraduate student of environmental chemistry. <#/>He has been researching on it since September last year.
\par <#/>In his research, Gachago found two types of tuff. <#/>One which is sold in Biashara Street, Nairobi, in packets. <#/>This is imported. <#/>The other is local and is sold in crude form
 at Gikomba market. <#/>One packet of about 124 grams costs Sh4. <#/>A similar amount of the local tuff coasts 50 cts. <#/>The imported one is called <ea/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 mahti}{\fs24\lang2057 .
\par <#/>Gachago's findings show that }{\i\fs24\lang2057 <ea/>mahti}{\fs24\lang2057  has low levels of iron, manganese, zinc and zirconium when compared with the local one. <#/>The elements of calcium, potassium and rubidium were not detected in a }{
\i\fs24\lang2057 <ea/>mahti}{\fs24\lang2057  sample.
\par <#/>On the other hand, there were some elements found in }{\i\fs24\lang2057 <ea/>mahti}{\fs24\lang2057  which were not found in the local soil. <#/>They were chromium, titanium and nickel.
\par <#/>The theory behind pregnant women craving for tuff is that they may be having iron deficiency in the blood. <#/>Since the woman is catering for her and the growing baby's needs, she needs a higher supply.
\par <#/>Since other animals reproduce, do they have a similar craving?
\par <#/>Gachago's observation is that when cows have sodium and calcium deficiency, they are seen developing strange appetite for such objects as bones and washing soap.
\par <#/>His research has been done on 28 femal
e rats divided into two groups. <#/>Seventeen of them which were experimental were fed on the ordinary rat food (rabbit pellets) plus grounded tuff mixed with the food. <#/>The remaining eleven were fed only on rat food.
\par <#/>Among the things observed in the two groups was a difference in the weight gain. <#/>Rats receiving tuff gained weight from an average of 74 grammes to 129 grammes. <#/>This is an equivalent of 74 per cent gain.
\par <#/>This is much less compared to the weight gained by the control group of an average of 105 per cent. <#/>That is from 74 grammes to 151 grammes.
\par <#/>Another observation was that the control group had well-groomed fur and were very active. <#/>The tuff-fed animals appeared lethargic and their fur coats were rough.
\par <#/>Looking at the breakdown of the metals found in tuff. <#/>Gachago says there are some like titanium whose role in the body is not known. <#/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 <Ea/>mahti}{\fs24\lang2057  has about five per cent titanium.
\par <#/>As far as health implications of eating tuff are concerned. <#/>Gachago says that chromium is useful in the clotting of blood. <#/>Above its useful limits, it can cause lung and liver cancer.
\par <#/>Iron at low level assists in the manufacturing of blood but high concentration leads to liver cirrhosis and lungs siderosis (fibrosis of the lungs).
\par <#/>Lead on the other hand has no useful effect, is toxic and can lead to mental retardation of the baby. <#/>The baby is also likely to have deformed teeth.
\par <#/>Gachago who says that the research is still continuing adds that he is not quite sure why some women get addicted to tuff even long after delivery.
\par <#/>Women who chew tuff say they just feel nice when they chew it, that they are not sure why they do it, that they feel a little thirsty until they eat some. <#/>Tuff lovers have a space in their handbags specifically reserved for it.
\par <#/>A women whose last child was born more than six years ago says she still cherishes the taste of tuff since her last pregnancy. <#/>She adds that the desire for it becomes intolerable when it rains.
\par <#/>Da
nger of toxicity aside, tuff eaters stand a chance of introducing parasites like worms into their system. <#/>Dr. Ndwiga Mwachandi of Canaan Medical Stores does not see this as the greatest threat since most of the women dig deeper into the soil. <#/>This
 means they get sterile soil that is devoid of worms.
\par <#/>But he says that eating soil at random could introduce worms and bacteria into the body.
\par <#/>The soil especially in agricultural areas could be contaminated with dangerous chemicals. <#/>Excess of a mineral such as silica is associated with a certain type of elephantiasis, he says.
\par <#/>Heavy metals like lead and mercury mixed with the soil can lead to diseases, he adds.
\par <#/>The doctor says he does not know exactly what causes the craving for the soil but recounts an experience that puzzled him.
\par <#/>It was a case of a woman who had fibroids (muscular swellings on the walls of the uterus). <#/>She had an extreme craving for the soil. <#/>It was recommended that the uterus be removed. <#/>Once it was removed, the urge immediately ended.
\par <#/>"In her case, I do not know whether it was a message from the uterus to the brain behaving as if it had a baby," he says.
\par <#/>He suggests
 that there might be lack of iron in the body's "granary" due to a woman not having been taking a balanced diet. <#/>He however expresses surprise that children suffering from marasmus and kwashiokor do not crave for the soil due to a similar deficiency.

