\par <I> <h> }{\fs24 <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 Parasitic diseases defy vaccines </}{\fs24\lang2057 h>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>The eradication of many diseases such as smallpox and to some extent measles and polio can be emphatically attributed to vaccination programmes.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 
However, the success recorded in developing vaccines against infections caused by viruses has not been found in development of vaccines against parasitic infections caused by protozoa such as malaria, and by worms such as schistosomiasis (bilharzia) and l
eishmaniasis. <#/>The main reason behind this is said to be the relative complexity of parasites compared to viruses.
\par <#/>The complexity of parasitic organisms has contributed not only to some difficulties in diagnosis of infections, but has also imposed c
onstraints upon designing of vaccination strategies. <#/>A major aspect of this complexity is the ability to evade or modify the immune response of the host.
\par <#/>To date, there are over 200 parasitic worms known to infect man. <#/>This perhaps is one reason why it is difficult to make an unequivocal identification in infected individuals and the number and type of parasites present.
\par <#/>Of the over 200, the most popular with researchers so far has been the schistosome and filariasis-causing worms. <#/>Their method of transmission have }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\fs24\lang2057 
 justified the need for intervention through vaccines. <#/>Well-focused attention on control of parasitic infections has however been jeopardized by low morality and high morbidity associated with the diseases, such as filariasis and schistosomiasis.

\par <#/>Despite the low mortality these infections still provoke severe disability through lesions and malnutrition, or blindness in the case of filarial infections.
\par <#/>With the advent of AIDS, the consequences of chronic parasitic infection can be expected to worsen, due to the suppressed immune system associated with AIDS.
\par <#/>Most research efforts towards development of a vaccine against parasitic infections in the last decade has been directed towards developing a vaccine against malaria, especially the parasite }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Plasmodium falciparum}{\fs24\lang2057 
. <#/>These efforts have been given more impetus in the wake of revelations that }{\i\fs24\lang2057 P. falciparum}{\fs24\lang2057 
 can be resistant against chemotherapy, especially with chloroquine. <#/>The first occurrence of Chloroquine-resistant Plasmodium falciparum (CRPF) in Kenyans was recorded in 1982.
\par <#/>At the moment, malaria exacts a huge toll in mortality and morbidity in Africa and is the leading killer disease in children, claiming a million children each year.
\par <#/>The disease occurs after a person is bitten by the anopheles mosquito vector which carries mature sporozoites in its salivery glands. <#/>The sporozoites ente
r the victim's liver and later red blood cells. <#/>This infection of the red blood cells is what presents itself clinically as malaria.
\par <#/>Research efforts aim at developing a vaccine that could block the invasion of the liver, blood cells, inhibit the development of the disease and prevent transmission.
\par <#/>Ideally then, the vaccine would consist of at least three antigens, to act against the three stages.
\par <#/>Schistosomiasis is thought to rank second to malaria among major parasitic diseases in terms of morbidity and mortality. <#/>Despite the development of an effective drug }{\i\fs24\lang2057 (Praziquantel)}{\fs24\lang2057 
 this status has not officially lowered. <#/>The situation in Africa is not likely to change, especially given the continued expansion of irrigated agricultural projects such as the Mwea Project in Embu.
\par <#/>Researchers at the Kenya Medical <-/Reserch> Institute (KEMRI) are at the moment doing a socially oriented study that aims at encouraging the community to prevent infection (Primary Health care). <#/>Scientists have
 estimated that currently more than 2 million Kenyans have been infected with bilharzia.
\par <#/>One problem with treating schistosomiasis with drugs is the prevalence of re-infection especially in young children, necessitating repeated treatment and sometimes indefinite surveillance.
\par <#/>Another common parasitic infection is leishmaniasis. <#/>In Kenya, this disease is prevalent in parts of Machakos, Kitui, Meru, Bungoma, Baringo, West Pokot, Laikipia and Turkana districts. <#/>The disease appears in two forms: }{\i\fs24\lang2057 
cutaneous leishmaniasis and visceral leishmaniasis}{\fs24\lang2057 
. <#/>The former presents as solitary and multiple disfiguring lesions on exposed parts of the body, while the latter attacks the liver, bone-marrow and spleen, resulting in a distended abdomen in the victim.
\par <#/>The current method of diagnosis of }{\i\fs24\lang2057 visceral leishmaniasis}{\fs24\lang2057  in Kenya which is a painful and risky technique involving removal of fluids from the spleen, through suction. <#/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 Visceral leishmaniasis}{
\fs24\lang2057  can be fatal if not treated early.
\par <#/>The disease i
s spread by a nocturnally active insect known as the sandfly. <#/>The treatment currently in use is unsuitable for most Third World countries since the drugs are expensive and require administration over a long period of time. <#/>Moreover, the victim sti
ll suffers from the everlasting scars in the case of }{\i\fs24\lang2057 cutaneous leishmaniasis}{\fs24\lang2057 .
\par <#/>One method of intervention that has been tried has been }{\i\fs24\lang2057 "leishmanization"}{\fs24\lang2057 . <#/>This is deliberate infection with leishmania to induce long-lasting immunity against }{\i\fs24\lang2057 cutaneous leishmaniasis}{
\fs24\lang2057 
. <#/>This method has been tried in USSR and Israel. <#/>In Iran, where other control methods failed, the high incidence of the disease along the Iran-Iraq war zone led authorities to give live inoculum to recruits and volunteers before sending
 them to endemic areas.
\par <#/>Side by side with the search for vaccines has been the development of anti-parasitic drugs. <#/>With parasitic vaccines still being elusive, manufacturing companies have continued to bring in new and better anti-parasitic drugs into the market.
\par <#/>The vaccine however still would be more ideal, principally because it would be prophylactic in its effects, that is, it would prevent development of disease. <#/>Few anti-parasitic drugs have significant chemoprophylactic activity and 
on the token that prevention is better than cure, vaccines would be <-/preferrable>.
\par <#/>Another advantage of the vaccine would be that while drugs require frequent dosing schedules (daily or weekly), a vaccine would provide protection f
or months, years or even for life. <#/>This means that a vaccine would be less expensive and more appropriate logistically.
\par <#/>The other problem is that some infections develop resistance to drugs, such as has been the case with chloroquine resistant }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Plasmodium falciparum}{\fs24\lang2057 .
\par <#/>Drugs, too, have their advantages over vaccines in that at times they can be used to prevent as well as cure diseases. <#/>Secondly with drugs, no intervention is necessary in healthy people. <#/>Also, vaccines tend to require refrig
eration, unlike most drugs.
\par <#/>It is important to note, however, that the presence of vaccines would not mean that the infections will disappear. <#/>Many good vaccines are still not universally employed, even when they are relatively cheap. <#/>Vaccines 
against poliomyelitis and measles, for instance, are still not fully utilised.
\par <#/>For developing countries, probably the most urgent control methods should be non-invasive, such as improvement in housing, sewage disposal and water supply.
\par <#/>This is the 
approach that is being followed by KEMRI field researchers at Mwea and Kwale. <#/>The emphasis is on community education, construction of latrines and bath units in the rice paddies and villages, construction of wells and of course treatment of infected p
