\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 A general lull seems to be hanging over cypress aphids, the much publicised environmental problem that sparked off anxiety countrywide recently.
\par <#/>It appears the pest outbreak no longer exists and all the hue and cry made was only alarmist.
\par <#/>Since the second half of last year, the cypress <-/aphidsoutbreak> sparked anxiety and fear because of the extensive potential it indicated in destroying all the green cover in this country.
\par <#/>Well nurtured and trimmed hedges turned brown and age-old forests gave in to a monster that took the very guardians of the treasured green cover by storm.
\par <#/>Within months of identification, the monster was spreading like bonfire - from Narok, Kiambu Nairobi, Murang'a, Nyeri, Meru, Nyandarua, everywhere. <#/>It had first been sighted at Kiserian in Ngong.
\par <#/>The anxiety expressed was as alarming as it was scaring. <#/>Perhaps closer Aids.
\par <#/>Farmers and foresters went scrounging for emergency solutions. <#/>They found it in the form of chemical sprays which gave some consolation. <#/>But not a lasting one.
\par <#/>Well, that anxiety has since subsided, at least for the majority of the Kenyan public who have little understanding of this monster. <#/>There has been less talk about it probably because some of the hedges and planta
tions have slowly begun to turn green.
\par <#/>The farmers are no doubt heaving a sigh of relief thinking the problem is solved.
\par <#/>But the monster has only been down, not out.
\par <#/>Cypress aphid, a yellowish-brown insect with a body size similar to a body louse, is still around.
\par <#/>But the little green cover that has picked up is only an evidence that it has subsided. <#/>Scientists who have been monitoring its trends within and out are attributing the low infestation to weather trends.
\par <#/>"The cold and rainy weather has left many of the aphids dead and the reproduction capability lower, says Jackson Maina, a senior forest officer in the department of forestry in Nairobi.
\par <#/>Showers, he says, have a tendency to wash them down to the ground.
\par <#/>But the cold and rainy weather lasts only <-/upto> July and it is expected that the aphids outbreak will pick up as soon as the weather becomes warmer again.
\par <#/>"What we have had in the last few months is only a break in the past months but the potential problem is still as bad," Maina says.
\par <#/>"We already have reports of fresh infestation in warmer areas that had none at all."
\par }{\fs24 <#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 That includes Taita Taveta district and a reinfestation in some parts of Baringo which have started to warm up.
\par <#/>"If you see trees recovering, it means that the reproduction process of aphids has slowed down. <#/>But not necessarily wiped out," says Maina.
\par <#/>A recent report by the Kenya Forestry Research Institute's (KEFRI) director, Dr Jeff Odera and E.K. Mutitu, states that peak popul
ation occurs between October and December. <#/>They also observe that misty areas like Kinale, Kitale, Molo, Londiani and others, have a lower aphid population.
\par <#/>"There is strong evidence that heavy rains and the hot dry season influence the development of aphid population resulting in an oscillating pattern," the report states.
\par <#/>This weather-related pattern has also been observed in Malawi where the first occurrence of the aphid in Africa was reported between 1986 and 1987.
\par <#/>The aphid has <-/todate> infested between 1500 and 2000 hectares of cypress forests in that country and spread also to Burundi, Rwanda and Tanzania.
\par <#/>In Kenya, the outbreak spread to a substantial part of the country and damaged 200,000 hectares of cypress species, in exotic and indigenous forests, plantations, hedges and woodlots.
\par <#/>The remaining 310,000 hectares of green cover - 200,000 indigenous trees, 80,000 exotic plantation and 30,000 of hedges and woodlot remain threatened.
\par <#/>"This is a big loss," Maina says.
\par <#/>
In order to arrest the problem, the department of Forestry in collaboration with Kefri and ICIPE, has established a project called Sustainable Integrated Management of the Cypress Aphid Project for Kenya, which is intended to undertake short and long term
 control measures to contain the problem.
\par <#/>The project is however at its early stages and is awaiting funds to enable it operate efficiently.
\par <#/>"We require 8.6 million US dollars for the five year-project," Maina who is also the deputy manager of the project says.
\par <#/>They have raised 2.75 million US dollars from Food and Agricultural Organisation, FAO, International Development Agency, IDA, U
nited Nations Development Programme, UNDP, and <-/Finish> International Development Agency, FINIDA, who have <-/channeled> the funds through the World Bank.
\par <#/>"Our first concern is to undertake short term measures which will contain the current emergency of the aphids problem," he says.
\par <#/>But they also want to research on the biological management approach against the aphid which he says may offer a more lasting solution than the chemical approach.
\par <#/>The latter involves the spraying of the aphid with chemicals.
\par <#/>"We have realised that the chemical approach may not be the long-lasting solution," he says.
\par <#/>They now want to introduce a natural enemy or predator - a wasp from Europe, where the cypress aphid is native. <#/>But this will only be effect
ed when enough research has been done on it and its effects here. <#/>He says Europe has no problem with the cypress aphid because there is a natural way of getting rid of it there through the predator.
\par <#/>Chemical application has its own constraints in that the aphids could build resistance after a while and also could lead to accidental poisoning of people, animals and fish.
\par <#/>The chemicals are also very expensive.
\par <#/>Foresters have been using the chemical Ambush because the chemical is environmentally friendly.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj\keepn\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel0\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>But what are the chances of the predators wiping the aphids?
