\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>Some people may not know the relationship between kidneys and diet. <#/>Yet the kidneys are vital organs
. <#/>Without functioning kidneys, a single meal upsets your whole metabolic balance. <#/>Metabolism is the physical and chemical changes occurring in the body. <#/>It includes food digestion.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Some important functions of the kidneys are: 
\par * Maintenance of composition and volume of the blood 
\par * Regulation of osmotic pressure 
\par * Regulation of electrolytes such as sodium (salt) potassium and <-/maintaing> water balance.
\par <#/>A normal kidney produces urine in normal volumes and concentration. <#/>This permit
s elimination of excess water and solutes such as salt and other by-products of food metabolism. <#/>An example is urea which is a by-product of protein break-down. <#/>Kidneys also eliminate substances that would otherwise be toxic to the body. <#/>Only 
the liver exceeds the kidney in its metabolic activities.
\par <#/>Due to the crucial role of the kidney - regulating body fluids, conserving nutrients, water and excreting waste products - it is not surprising that renal or kidney diseases affect every system and tissue in the body.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {<#/>Let us look at the nutritional care of various kidney ailments. <#/>Renal diseases may be acute, sub-acute (latent) or chronic. <#/>They may also have many causes.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Disorders affect }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <+_the>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\fs24\lang2057 <-/matabolism> of nutrients and thei
r by-products. <#/>There may be decreased renal clearance of urea, sodium (salt) potassium, mineral elements mostly prevalent in fruits, and calcium mainly found in milk and milk products. <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>
There may also be inability of the kidney to conserve nutrients such as protein.
\par Nephritis or Brights disease is used as a general term to indicate any altered kidney function caused by inflammation or degenerative changes.
\par Acute }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 glomerulo-nephritis }{\v\fs24\lang2057 is a disorder frequently found in children and young adults. It leads to infections such as tonsillitis, pneumonia, respiratory infections and scarlet fever.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v In some individuals, the renal infection is so mild that there is no awareness of the disease. Symptoms resulting from permanent damage may appear much later. Others n
otice some swelling of the ankles and puffiness around the eyes, headaches, anorexia, nausea and vomiting. Varying degrees of hypertension and dimness of vision. There is usually a diminished urinary output (oliguria) hematuria (blood in urine). Full reco
very is most likely when treatment is prompt and appropriate.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v\fs24\lang2057 
Nutritional care works towards maintaining a good nutritional status. During the acute phase of this illness, it is a bit unrealistic to meet all the nutritional requirements. In acute glomerulo-
nephritis, protein and potassium should not be restricted unless there is uremia (retention of by-products of protein metabolism) or potassium retention in the blood (hyperkalemia) is present.
\par If oedema is present, salt (sodium) intake should be restricted
 until congestion or oedema is alleviated. After this solution, there is usually no further need for salt restriction. In the presence of oliguria, fluids are restricted to prevent further oedema.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {\v Chronic glomerulonephritis may be asymptomatic for months o
r even years. This disease may be detected only by laboratory tests. As the disease progresses, there is proteinuria (protein in the urine) and blood in the urine, which may result into low protein in the blood as well anaemia.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\v\fs24\lang2057 This inability of the kidney
 to get rid of the metabolic wastes amounts to their retention at toxic levels. In this stage, nutritional intervention, (as well as medical treatment) is extremely crucial. Primary objectives of nutritional care are to:
\par * Minimise the production of waste products.
\par * To restore good nutritional status by replacing lost urine. 
\par * Promote potassium balance. 
\par * Control body swelling (oedema) and hypertension. 
\par * To provide a palatable diet with easily digested foods.
\par When there is retention of protein wastes in the blood, the protein intake is reduced to a minimum requirement (approximately 40 grams. To prevent breakdown of body proteins, enough carbohydrates and fats are given.
\par Another kidney ailment is known as <-_nephrotic><+_nephritic> syndrome. It is characterised by oedema, severe protein loss in the urine, hypoalbuminemia and high  cholesterol levels in the blood. Hypertension may occur in the disease state.
\par Unlike most other kidney ailments, this condition calls for high protein intake. It also needs a high calorie intake. The kidney is usually able to eliminate metabolic wastes.
\par If nutrition intervention is not <-/aggresive> enough, tissue or muscle wastage and malnutritio
n may result. Malnutrition causes further complication by causing oedema on a decreased blood flow. In some cases, adequate protein and food intake may not be possible due to anorexia, nausea and vomiting.
\par To receive the proper nutritional care, you need to ask your medical doctor the details of your kidney ailment.
